title: For Trade:  Inland (GM) M1 Carbine
location: RTP, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent: ** Note: I am really only interested in trading this for an IBM M1 Carbine. I expect this to take a while and that is OK. If I can't find an IBM carbine to trade for, I am happy keeping this gun indefinitely. The only reason I'd sell or trade it for any other deal is if it was an offer I couldn't refuse, ie significantly in my favor. **Receiver is marked "INLAND DIVISION." Barrel is marked "INLAND DIVISION" "GENERAL MOTORS" "6-45". This means it was made after V-E Day, before V-J Day during the latter days of WWII. Given its manufacture date, it is almost guaranteed that it saw no action in WWII, but it's entirely likely it went to Korea and perhaps Vietnam. The Battle of Okinawa took place the same month it was made. Perhaps the people who made it were imagining the carbines being used for the dreaded invasion of Japan.Metal is parkerized with no rust or significant issues, though there are a few scuffs. Bore is beautiful. Stock has no markings (typical of an armorer swapping out a damaged stock). Stock is walnut with what I believe is the original finish. It also has minor scuffs but no cracks or gouges. It has a bayonet lug, typical of late-war carbines.
